<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-159-454 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 711 029</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 6 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Chrysler announces gasoline-methanol mixture sensor. (ChryslerSmart Sensor)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mallory, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chrysler Corp. (Innovations).andO;Ticker:    C.andO;Topic:     Automobile IndustryNew TechniqueSensorsProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CHRYSLER ANNOUNCES GASOLINE-METHANOL MIXTURE SENSOR 05/06/91 HIGHLAND PARK,MICHIGAN, U.S.A., 1991 MAY 6 (NB) -- Chrysler Corporation has announced thatit has developed a workable sensor that allows any fuel tank mixture ofgasoline and up to 85 percent methanol with no noticeable performance ordrivability difference.andM;The device, called the Smart Sensor, is reportedly the invention of twoChrysler electrical engineers, one of whom is retired.andP;  Says FrancoisCastaing, engineering VP, &quot;Our Smart Sensor puts the 'flex' in flexible-fuelvehicles.andP;  Many flexible-fuel vehicles being tested today are actuallyalternative fueled vehicles with the capability to run on either gasoline,methanol, or a specific combination of the two, but not a continual variationof any of those.&quot;andM;The Chrysler statement said the brain of the Smart Sensor is a built inmicroprocessor that includes all the electronics required to process thesensor's information and relax signals to the engine computer.andP;  The systemalso includes diagnostics, a fuel-sensing reservoir, a waterproof electricalconnector and a rugged mounting.andP;  The entire device fits inside anickel-coated plastic housing about the size of a audio cassette.andM;Chrysler says they have been researching various methanol concentrationsensors, including optical sensors.andP;  The Smart Sensor detects changes in thedielectric constant which then signals the necessary information to theengine computer.andM;(Jim Mallory/19910505/Press Contact: Jason Vines, Chrysler, 313-956-5346)</TEXT><